title.narrative: CAPACITY TO PROVIDE & UTILISE GENDER RESPONSIVE SERVICES ON HIV

description.narrative: Health facilities, communities and caregivers have improved capacity to provide and utilize gender-responsive services for children and adolescents living with HIV and pregnant and breastfeeding women., which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids (Covid), Operations Support To Programme Delivery. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2025, parents and children, with a focus on the most vulnerable, have access to equitable, integrated, quality essential health, nutrition and HIV services including during emergencies.

sector.narrative: Programme support for PMTCT including for triple elimination, viral load monitoring, retention in care, infant feeding, PreP among HIV-negative women and negative partners, family planning and partner testing

title.narrative: Health facilities, communities and caregivers have improved capacity to provide and utilize gender-responsive services for childrenand adolescents living with HIV and pregnant and breastfeeding women.

description.narrative: UNICEF supported with financial and technical inputs the Ministry of Health (MOH) and two Non-Government Organizations (NGO), Baylor and Siphilile, to capacitate 31 health facilities, 49 mentor mothers and 40 caregivers in four regions. This was to provide and utilize gender-responsive services for 867 children and adolescents, 2,574 people living with HIV and 8,910 pregnant and breastfeeding women living with HIV to reach elimination of mother to child transmission (EMTCT) of HIV and syphilis including during the COVID-119 pandemic and the civil unrest.; | Status:On-track | As-of Date:10/01/2022
